equilibrium and misalignment an assessment of the rmb exchange rate from 1978 to 1999 siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home publications profile display equilibrium and misalignment an assessment of the rmb exchange rate from 1978 to 1999 type scid working paper 127 author s zhang xiaopu published 02 1 02 region china download pdf abstract exchange rate misalignment tends to disrupt the economic growth of developing countries and persistent overvaluation may even lead to currency crises since the asian financial crises in 1998 economists and policy makers have been concerned with whether or not the china currency renminbi yuan rmb is overvalued based on new developments in the equilibrium exchange rate theory this paper develops equilibrium real exchange rate erer and behavioral equilibrium exchange rate beer models for rmb by using cointegration analysis the hodrick prescott hp filter and other econometrics techniques the estimation results show that the exchange rate of rmb is close to the equilibrium level in 1999 towards the end this paper analyzes the trajectory of rmb exchange rate misalignment since 1978 and makes an assessment of rmb exchange rates the author suggests gradual reforms in exchange rate policies stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
